<div class="testimonial">
    <h2>No joke, this class was life changing</h2>
    <img src="<%= asset_path('students/rania-300x300.png') %>" alt="Hikma Academy Image 10">
    <p>Over the past year I learned way more about Islam than I thought. My first day, as usual, I did not want to be there because I thought it was like every other class I been to. Less than I know, no joke, this class was life changing. Throughout the week you lose yourself and forget your Deen, but you had every Sunday to realize yourself. For sure my favorite thing about being a part of this amazing journey is the relationship with my classmates and teacher. All of my classmates are my friends and we make the best out of the class. We even hangout out of class. And for the teacher, she is a very easy person to talk to without having the fear of “she will not understand me” I have been in this class for 2 years and I never see myself not taking it.</p>
</div>

<div class="testimonial">
    <h2>My spirit is at rest</h2>
    <img src="<%= asset_path('students/hkfjj-e1474528249891-300x300.png') %>" alt="Hikma Academy Image 11">
    <p>I have been going to Hikma academy since it started and I have never felt so content before on a Sunday morning. Usually on a Sunday morning am either thinking about school the next day or doing chores at home. Hikma gives me chance to be myself. Express myself the way I want to without being provoked. But most importantly I love the knowledge that soaks into my brain when am there, I feel this massive weight being lifted away from my shoulders and being replaced with peace and integrity. I pick these two words because it basically summarizes my whole stay at Hikma. Integrity because growing up as a kid I didn’t know who I was, what I stand for, what’s my pride, who to trust who not to trust, what to do in difficult situations and so on. But now I know what my strong morals are and now I can live off of it .And peace because when am there I feel disconnected from this dunia. Disconnected from the drama at school, homework, chores you name it. Instead my spirit is at rest, now I don’t know if it’s because of me connecting with my lord or if it’s because I feel the presence of the angels around us, but I know for a fact that I feel tranquil from head to toe. Mash Allah I have learned many things from there not only the tafseer in the Quran but how to live in the west as a young African American teenager. I can’t say this enough but I really enjoy her class she has a way of explaining things that make so much sense, not just some stuff she looked up from Wikipedia she actually spends all of her free time going to halaka’s and doing whole lot of researches just so that we can understand and benefit from it. So I end up leaving the center with a little knowledge every Sunday</p>
</div>

<div class="testimonial">
    <h2>Filling a void with Quran</h2>
    <img src="<%= asset_path('students/muslimah-silhouette-e1399917788374.jpg') %>" alt="Hikma Academy Image 14">
    <p>I initially signed up for Hikma Academy’s Tafseer class hoping to gain more closeness to Allah through understanding His book. There was a void within me that desired a more personal and intimate relationship with that Qur’an, one that would act as the foundation to which I nurture my faith. I also knew I needed to cultivate that relationship on a more consistent and structured basis, something a weekly class would perfectly offer. What I truly value most about this experience is being surrounded by a phenomenal group of sisters who all are seeking that same closeness to the Qur’an. Throughout this journey of reflecting on the words of Allah, it is through their individual wisdom that I am also able to learn from. Whether it’s through our collective discussions, random tangents, or heartfelt class reflections, these sisters have become some of my most cherished friends and acquaintances. Ustadha Kaltun’s tafseer class has allowed me to gain better insight into my own character by assessing the values and principles Allah calls us to through His book. Each week I am challenged to apply the teachings of that particular surah and use its wisdom to refine the relationship I have with Allah, with myself, and with the loved ones in my life. Each week I am challenged through the Qur’an to be the best version of myself, the version my Rabb ultimately wants for me. It continues to be a journey of growth, self-realization and transformation – alhamdulillah thumma alhamdulillah. I am forever indebted to our teacher Kaltun Karani who is the vessel Allah has chosen to teach us through. May Allah continue to bless and expand her efforts and the mission of Hikma Academy.</p>
    <div class="author">Zuleikha Suleiman</div>
</div>

